ogy during the Second World War. Several essays are particularly relevant to contemporary concerns. A history of sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) in Canada, extended to include present-day research, reveals underlying flaws in the approach to STDs taken by Canadian governments and the medical establishment. The comparative development of health insurance in Canada and the United States is discussed in another essay. Other authors provide a historical and critical review of a key assumption of Canadian Medicare: that universal first-dollar coverage will enhance equity in the use of health services and in health status. In addition to David Naylor, who writes the Introduction, the contributors are Robin F. Badgley, Jay Cassel, Terry Copp, Raisa B. Deber, Colin D. Howell, Stephen J. Kunitz, Desmond Morton, Eugene Vayda, Samuel Wolfe, and Judith Young.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBadgley, Robin F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassel, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopp, Terry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid Naylor, C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeber, Raisa B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowell, Colin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuniz, Stephen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorton, Desmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVayda, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfe, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoung, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel